## What (probably) happened in 1.0.3
In order to optimize the validation flow we chose to generate the reference answer concurrently in a background thread while waiting for the network to respond. This utilizes the 10 second timeout period and prevents the validator being idle in that time, and as a result the time for each forward step is reduced by 40%. We tested these changes for 48 hours on mainnet with our validator (no weight setting) and everything looked awesome.

There was a flaw in the design which is that we were **awaiting** the reference generation, thus not allowing the bittensor middleware to attach important metadata such as elapsed time and and status code until the reference was created.

Now, there is a strong dependence of validator tokens/second on the specific machine that validators are running. I ran those tests on an A100 and reference generation never exceeded 10s, while on many other machines the reference generation can and does exceed 10s. As a result, the **validators were blocking bittensor middleware and forcing timeouts**.

We're going to take today and tomorrow to review the issues in more detail and then we will announce the next minor release early next week.

Cheers,
